nodes.title: Step 4 - Sparse Control Options
widgets_values:
This area is preparing for sparce controls

Skip for sparce controls allows you to lower the number of frames you bring in as keyframes from the original image.  The more you skip here, the less keyframes the video will have when generating and can lose movement you are looking to copy, look at the preview to see if the lower FPS video is sutible.

Default here is 2, can do less, but again, the video can get choppy when you dont have enough keyframes.

Spread Methood Is set defailt to center, but can use uniform in some cases.  I cant tell you when but some videos like uniform, others center.

Info of the Keyframes is here with the total frames to be rendered.  Also the Target FPS with the Sparse FPS is shown.  

You can resize the video here for processing.  Defaults to 448x448 so the max one side can be is 448.  it will resize keeping proportions.  You can change this to the max size you want.

Masking to the left is the next optional step

nodes.title: Step 12 - Upscale Controlnets
widgets_values:
Upscale controls

Lineart and tile optoins.  Not always needed.  Try without first. 

I use scaled weights of .825 - 9 for both these controls.

Using these prevents fixing many things it will focus on detailing.  If not enabled it can fix some things... or make them worse.

Using no controls here uses LESS vram than the first step even at 2x upscale.  Adding 1 control will use about the same as the first step. and adding 2 uses even more vram.

This allows you to increase the fps by the multiple you select here

Use this if you are using a 5fps gif  file or really anything lower than 10 and want to increase the fps of the ouput video.

nodes.title: Step 2 - Animate diff Model Loading and settings
widgets_values:
Load in the motion module for animate diff here
I use V3 i am not sure if others work.

Context options can be default standard uniform or Looped Uniform

Use standard uniform unless you have a looped source video.

nodes.title: Step 8 - Prompting
widgets_values:
This is just a simple prompt with 2 helper groups if you are not going to use the regional prompting

Prompt anything with the normal negative and postive and you would normaly for a video

tagger prompting help 
- this will just tag your IP adapter image with tagger and add it to the prompt, it can help consistancy, but hurt animations depending what tags are used.
- I use this often, but i always check tags and excluded anything that i dont want.
- auto excludes keywords in your manual prompt automaticly.

Color Prompting tokens
- this is 2 simple token boxes to seperate colors.  colors bleed less when you add them as seperate tokens to the other prompt items expecially when you heavilly weight the colored items.  (red shoes:1.3), (black hat:1.3)  put in 2 different boxes.

nodes.title: Step 11 - Upscale IP adapter
widgets_values:
This allows you to set a different IP model/strength for the upscale.  It can help to lower weights on the base to get the animation correct and use this to properly get the character with a stronger model.

2 masks available.  Recomended to mask subject here if you can from below.

nodes.title: Step 13 - Upscale Generation
widgets_values:
Upscale Generation.

Uses LCM can bypass in the checkpoint loaders.

Steps 4-8 LCM SGM Uniform

For simple movments, dont use a controlnet to test, as it tends to fix more and detail more.

If you are doing a dance, or fast moving animation, adding line or tile controls will help it follow the proper animation.

nodes.title: Step 5 - Optional Masking
widgets_values:
Sam options allow you to change the sam model

All point editors should populate with the first frame of the video on the first run, Disable all renders to set up before starting render groups.

Set masking size sets the size of the video sent to the masking area, it allows you to resize it to be smaller not take as long or use as much memory.  I believe sam 2 wants 1024, but less works, defaults to 512 max on either side.  The larger you go can help in detections.

Masks are all resized after to a set number you set here as well,  I used 320 px max for the mask size after detect.  Larger here requires more memory but can be slightly more accurate.

This area offers 3 subject mask groups using SAM 2 to mask the video. 
Any masks generated here are combined into the suject masks


These masks are not needed, but allow the following

1. background replacement can be used if not a moving camera shot.
2. Mask certain areas to static RBG controls to fully copy certain areas of the video.  Because the Sparse controls dont hold things 100% and allow change you can mask certain background elements to hold to original video or generated background.
4. Masking ip adapters to different subjects (regional Prompting and ip)

How all the sam 2 masking groups work in this flow

When run, this flow will populate the same point editors with the first frame of the video.  

Using The points editor 
- Shift left Click to add green points
- Shift Right click to add red points
Reset if you have too many

To mask things here are my rules i go by to mask subjects

This is best done with the SAM2 option of individual objects DISABLED - defaults for subject masks
Subject masking (one or multiple)
-Place one green point on the face of the subject
-Place one red point on the background OR any other subject faces

This can be done for each subject seperate

This is not limited to just people.  Dogs, cats, cars, balls, can all be masked and included in the subject masks.  All masks are saved seperate for IP adapter, and combined for the overall subject masks. 

This can seperate people, or anything else SAM 2 can mask, 1 person, a car and a tree... sure.  Just set the masking points on what you want to mask

Context stride, use 1 for anything below 32 frames it will error if using more than 2 for some reason.

can use 2 for more.


Ok from what i can tell, if you try to use video with less frames than the context length * stride it will error

Meaning 20 frames, stride 2 fails and will crash comfy strait up.... i dont know if this is a bug in comfy or animate diff or if its just supposed to hard crash when you get this wrong

I recomended 1-2 for stride here, as the sparse controls dont mix well with this.

Context overlap can go as high as 8.

nodes.title: Step 8 - Regeional Prompting
widgets_values:
This allows you to set an ip image and prompt for each mask you generated and the background if wanted.  I dont recommend using main IP with regional.

This allows all IP adapter options for each mask, and allows a prompt.  

Adding prompts can increase the gen time by multiples expecially if you are using more than 1 mask.  

You can use all IPs connected to each mask and NOT prompt to the mask to save time if it works.  It really helps to prompt but the time needed is much higher.

Each area uses a lower number of masks required for the full video as set by your sparse controls.  Frame interpolation of the masks is available.. and works well.  But it was added before i saw it was not needed most of the time.  Do not enable the mask frame interpolations unless you need to.  It can help with fast motions that change a lot between frames but its not perfect and it works without doing it usually

Adding a background image ref can really help background generations, but can also hurt subject animations if you are limiting the subject to the masks.  Ensure your masks dont overwrite one another. You do not need to prompt to the background mask to get results.

You can try repacing your Main ip ref background with your loaded background.  This can have a very similar effect of using the background regional prompting.

Each mask has a image / prompt weight, change these as you see fit.  Change weight type to what works best for your video.  Start and end times can also be played with.

nodes.title: Step 9 - Base Generation
widgets_values:
Base generation using sparce controls.

LCM used but can bypass this in checkpoint options and us any.

Steps 0-4 to 0-12 depending on model used etc.

Shutterstock shows up, sometimes stronger than others, nothing i can do about that as the training data was crap.  Upscale can usually remove it if its not too strong.

If the video has stuttering, or wild jumping, this is due too the skip every being too high for that video segment or you need to change from uniform to center.  It does not have enough ref keyframes to mimic fast motions when skipping too many frames from the ref.

Fast motions in general are better done in a full video to video flow instead of this. Dancing, runnning, jumping, were all very very hard to capture. 

Using stonger RGB controls for a small number of steps (start:0 end:0.35) can allow you to hold tricky animations while still allowing for changing the subject.  

Changing the steps used here changes the values the start/end percents use for the controls.

Background notes

This can help hold backgrounds to an image you have uploaded or connect the original frames from the video with the background masks to help hold the backgrounds


This can cause animation problems, but also can help give a solid background without much morphing.  

You dont need to add a prompt usually, just the ip ref works well.  

Alternative to this is using the main ip adapter and placing your new subject on the new background.  This saves a ton of ram and can do just about as well as this background group but it only works with 1 subject.
1girl, (blue crop top, purple spandex pants:1.2), long sleeves, curly hair

nodes.title: Step 3 - Prepare Video
widgets_values:
To the left is the video loader, it loads from the comfyui/input folder.  Put any videos you want to use in that folder and refresh comfy to see changes.  Can load mp4 or .gif

Skip every
- this allows you to set the FPS of the output.  The fps of this preview is the fps the output will come out.  I use skip every 2 most of the time with 25-30fps videos for an effective fps of 12-15.  You can choose to skip none by entering 1 into the field.

Frame load cap
Limits the frames you bring in, allowing you to limit the video to smaller segments.

Skip first frames
- Allows you to start the clip at the frame you wish.

Change FPS allows you to change the fps up or down (0.5 half - 2.0 double)
This does not effect the frames generated so this can have the effect of slow motion/sped up animations

Multiply frames will multiply the frames in the generated video
 - usefull when you want to bring in ALL frames from the original video and increase the number of frames generated by using all the original frames as sparse controls for more frames than the original.  This can take 5fps .gif files using the full .gif frames as sparse, and generate 10-20fps outputs with 2-4 multiply frames, change the fps in this case to match, or can add slow motion etc.  

The fps is just the FPS the final frame count will run at, while multiply frames actually doubles/triples etc the frames you generate.  

1 is default for both

nodes.title: Step 6 - Background Replacements Optional
widgets_values:
When enabled this group removes the background of the video with the subject masks you created.  Then inserts the subject into a loaded image to replace the background.  This can work with static camera shots decently.  

In order to enable this you need to have made subject masks

nodes.title: Step 5 - Optional Masking
widgets_values:
This area offers 2 objects mask groups using SAM 2 to mask the video. 

If not using RGB controls, these masks and options have NO effect.  These are only to help color clothing/items when using stronger RGB controls to allow better color changes while still using higher strengths

These masks can however be used in static RGB/line controls to control animations.

These masks are not needed, and should only be enabled if you want to do either of the following

1.  Mask something to change its color.
 - Tint masks is available here allow 2 types 
  -- tint color
  -- full color replace
2. use the mask in the static rgb or lineart controls to better control animations.

This is used mostly when a clothing item has a large contrast with the rest of the video and gets coppied into the generation.  Changing its color to match what you want it to be or to match the surrounding colors can help remove it.

Example :  a person wearing a tie that contrasts with the rest of the outfit.  Can color the tie to the same as the outfit to help remove it.
Example 2 : can color all clothing to peach, or get the HEX of the skin color to remove clothing easier, and can help add different clothing.


How all the sam 2 masking groups work in this flow

When run, this flow will populate the same point editors with the first frame of the video.  

Using The points editor 
- Shift left Click to add green points
- Shift Right click to add red points
Reset if you have too many

To mask things here are my rules i go by

These are best done with the SAM2 option of individual objects ENABLED -  defaults for mask 1 and 2

Clothing masking
- Place a red point on the subjects face
- place a green point on the clothing item you want to mask
- if needed place another red point on any other clothing you dont want included.

Face Masking
- Place a green point on the subjects face
- place a red point on the subject clothing or body

Skin masking
- Place a green point on the subjects face and any seperated from the face, legs, arm only if you need to
- Place a red point on the subject clothing and hair

Hair masking
- Place a green point on the hair
- Place a red point on the subject face and body

These dont always work but they do 90% of the time if you play with the points.

Tint masks allows you to masks parts of the video (hair, clothing, skin) and tint them a certain color to use with the rgb controls.  This allows you to change colors of clothing and types much easier.

Replace masks allows you to replace the mask area with a more solid color, removing some clothing lines from the lineart generations.

The more points you place the longer it will take to segment the video.

Masks

You can connect any of these to the controls, i rarely do this but they are here.

nodes.title: Step 1 - Checkpoint and lora Loading
widgets_values:
Here yo can load in any Checkpoint you want to use, 

I use LCM lora you enable and load that here as well as the V3 animate diff lora. 

There is a lora stacker here to allow you to use up to 3 loras.

nodes.title: Step 7 - Ip adapter and regional conditioning
widgets_values:
Ip adapter ( main and regional prompting)

I recommend you use a photo similar to the video in its contents/stance/imagecrop

This is the main IP adapter, the model needs to be enabled to use any of the ip adapter options including the regional conditioning

Options for main ip

-Flip will flip your ip image
-Remove BG will remove the bg from the ip ref and leave a black background
-Replace BG will replace the background with your loaded background image.  This is only availible if you remove background
- Crop face 1 and 2, use 1 realistic, use 2 for anime.

Using the replace background for thie main ip can almost do as well as regional conditioning background ip adapter with much lower ram use.  This works best the closer your ref image is to the video pose and location in the frame.

V2 Beta - full control sparse (advanced)
WARNING - this is not an easy flow to follow atm, i made this to see how far i could take sparse controls and to test new ideas for my main videos workflow.  There are many options that are not fully explained and as such i recommend you use v1.1 until i can simplify many of this.  This beta is fully functional as far as i know, but can go wrong in many places if you are not familiar with all the things i am doing in it.  I have added many notes but i do not feel it will be enough to explain properly.  To use most of the advanced masking i would recommend 12gb vram, but basic use should be usable with 6 if not masking.

Use at own risk :p i am working on simplfying it for a release.  I will be honest i still dont understand why sparse masking works in ip adapter... 

- Changed loader to load from any folder
- added saving to save to a folder inside output folder called sparsevids/yourvideoname
- Added 3 optional subject mask groups
 - added save/load masks to reload previous (this can get confusing with sparse and skip everys)
- most previews can now save to predetermined folder.
- added 2 optional object mask tint/recolor groups
- added cropping/padding/fliping original video
- added Change FPS/Frames options
- added replace IP ref background
- added presize and after sizing for masking
- added Loader for upscale to skip the first step and load in videos saved from the base previously.
- added so many little things

- added Regional Conditioning for multiple subjects
 -- Ip ref image for any mask
 -- OPTIONAL prompt for each mask.


V1.1

- Changed the way tinting works, now cuts/pastes to properly tint objects.
- Added model options
- added ability to increase FPS of the generation with the same sparse controls.  This allows you to use source videos at 4-10 fps and generate the output at double/triple that.
- changed upscale masking to use the upscaled video, it changed nothing but it confused people.


Tips for use

You dont need masks... at ALL.. They are only there to use if you want.  Most videos should work strait out with no masks.  Subject masks are needed for background removal, and tinting and static RGB can use the object masks.  None of that is needed to generate.



Recommended videos on animate diff
https://www.youtube.com/@koalanation

Recommended videos on Ip adapter
https://www.youtube.com/@latentvision

nodes.title: Step 7 - Sparse Control net Options
widgets_values:
Here you can set the strengths of the controlnets and set any masks to the static rgb group

Subject BG Mask 1 and 2 available if created.

Static copy lineart / rgb
This can be used to full copy a masked section of the video that is morphing due to ip adaptor or any other reason.  Ip adapter is not masked at the base step so it can bleed into other objects morphing them or textuing them with your subject... This is not needed most of the time but can help anytime you have this issue.
RGB sparse tends to flash if set too strong (default uses soft scaled weights at 0.95)

This is done in a way to start at step 3 (default when the sparse RGB ends)

Example project has the girl getting out of water, this control was used to mask the side of the pool that she was getting out on to prevent it from trying to draw the girl below the area she should appear.  



Sparse RGB
This is an RGB control net that helps a lot with animation fludity, at high strengths it cant change much, and can nearly just full copy a video if it did not flash terribly.  This is why it starts at 0 and ends at 0.35.  (default step 3 of 8).  This tends to hold the animation quite well while allowing quite a bit of change to the subject.  You will notice the first 3 steps to nearly copy, but change drasticly at step 4.  IP adapter helps this.

Sparse Scribble
This is a Lineart control net that helps hold the animation after the RGB has ended while still allowing subject change.  This is used throughout the video at 0.8 strength, this can go down to 0.5 and up to 1.   At high strengths you will get a shutterstock logo... Its in the training data.  .8 minimizes this, but upscale can usually remove this if you dont use too strong of controls there.

You can use any linearts, they all work but different.  Scribble, lineart, pidinet, HED.  
Lower res works best IMO about 320 - 960.  But you can change that how you want.

This is the subject/background masks

You can frame interpolate them to use in the upscale if you would like to for some reason.

This save folder is inside comfyui/output/

Save folder name is the folder it will create inside this output folder defaults to SparseVids

Then it creates folders inside this for each different video generated.  This saves any of the previews to this folder.
1girl, 22 year old woman, naked, short black hair, black glasses, asian
1girl, 22 year old woman, auburn hair, naked

If you are using regional conditioning you choose what conditonings apply to the video.  The more you add here the longer the render time.  Adding all 5 will 3x the render time if not more and add vram requirements

The ip adapter is attached to all masks you enaable, you do not "need" to connect prompts here, but it helps.  

You can try prompting to the main first, with all subjects, the ip ref may direct the prompting to the right area.

Add the connections to the combine node as needed, each mask area can be connected or not.

Try to add as few as you can to the positive, each one after the main is masked.  If adding the BG and a subject you can try skipping main, it should work

If you are trying to do a 3 person separated 200+ frame video... good luck as the time needed will be large, my 3060, can do it... but VERY SLOW.

Adding the masked prompts makes the video much more stable and what you want, but takes 2-3 times as long to render this way. You choose what works best for you.
